<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Department for Education</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 22.11pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">welcomes the opportunity to give evidence to the Committee on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our work to improve children’s residential care.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 22.11pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In response to the Report of the Office of the Children's Commissioner's inquiry into child sexual exploitation in gangs and groups, and the All Party Parliamentary Group joint inquiry report on children who go missing from care, Ministers established three expert groups - the Task and Finish Group on Out of Area Placements, the Expert Group on Quality and the Data Working Group. The last of these reports was published on 23 April 2013.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 22.11pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government is now taking forward </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a wide-ranging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The consultation on regulatory reform has been the most prominent of those elements to date, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">set out </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the latest position</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, ahead of a full response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is however by no means the end of the Government’s endeavours in this area, and this paper will go on to set out our intention for further reform.</span></li></ol><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 7.1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Background</span></h2><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 22.11pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hildren’s residential care is used for a small proportion of looked after children. There were 68,110 looked after children at 31 March 2013, with only 4,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">930</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> children placed in a children’s home</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 22.11pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Children </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">placed in children’s homes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are mostly over the age of 12, and many have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">been placed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there as a result of their challenging behaviour</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Children who live in children’s homes have high levels of emotional and behavioural difficulties. A recent research study found that 38% of children living in homes had a statement of special educational needs; 62% had clinically significant mental health difficulties; 74% were reported to have been violent or aggressive in the past 6 months. Children who live in homes were found to have achieved lower attainment levels in Key Stage examinations than other children. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 22.11pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1,718 children’s homes in England were registered with Ofsted at 31 March 2013. Of these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 371 (22%) were local authority run and 1,347 (78%) were in the private or voluntary sector. This pattern of ownership has changed quickly; the proportion of places in LA-run provision decreased from 61% in 2001 to 35% in 2006</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 22.11pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Most LAs make use of children home provision outside of the LA boundary and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more than a third of children placed in children’s homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re placed more than 20 miles from their parental home. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For some children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">being placed in homes that are outside the local authority area and at a significant distance from their home communities will be appropriate, for example where children require specialist provision or where they will be at risk of continued involvement with gangs or sexual exploitation within their home communities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocal authorities and the children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who are placed out of boundary however </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">encounter a range of additional challenges and issues when children are at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a considerable distance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Notably,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> LAs are unable to rely on their local knowledge and intelligence about the quality of homes or the suitability of their location, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it can impact on social worker’s ability to regularly visit the child and monitor the quality of the placement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the distance between the child and their family may limit relationships and undermine the scope for work with the whole family</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Local provision is however not always available in the quantities required to satisfy the requirements.  There are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local authorities with no home provision in their area and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a further 9 had no private or voluntary sector run homes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 22.11pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Raising the standard of children’s residential care requires a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">broad </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The Government is undertaking action to drive improvements in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">safeguarding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and care</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inspection, the standard of the children’s homes workforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commissioning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and quality of private voluntary and public sector provision. </span></li></ol><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 7.1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">egulatory change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> to strengthen arrangements for safeguarding and supporting children</span></h2><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 22.11pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The reports referred to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">paragraph 2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highlighted failings in the safeguarding arrangements put in place by children’s homes and in local authority processes for commissioning residential care. Children placed in distant out of authority placements are especially vulnerable. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Government consulted on proposals for changes to strengthen the requirements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">safeguarding children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Children’s Homes Regulations 2001</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Care Planning, Placement and Case Review Regulations 2010 (the “Care Planning Regulations”)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and the Care Standards Act 2000 (Registration) (England) Regulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Formal consultation took place between 28 June and 17 September 2013. Over 250 professionals attended the consultation events and 252 written responses were received. The wide range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">responding to the consultation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local authorities, children’s homes providers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">voluntary organisations representing children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> were broadly in favour of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s ambition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. There was general agreement around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the need to introduce more effective safeguarding arrangements for looked after children in residential care</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and for improving the process that should be in place when children are placed outside of the authority responsible for their care. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A number of the proposals commanded strong support, including the proposals to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">require children’s homes to notify the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">area authority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the admission and discharge of children from the home;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">require existing homes to conduct an annual  “risk assessment” of the area in which the home is situated;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">include an explicit reference </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in Regulation 11 of the children’s homes regulations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to safeguarding in the list of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">responsibilities of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">registered managers ; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensure that the provider’s strategy for keeping a looked after child safe is included as a significant part of their placement plan.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Respondents to the consultation expressed a degree of concern about how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposals would work in practice. We are presently considering whether these concerns can be met through the refinement of the proposals or by providing additional support (such as guidance). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Examples </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of proposals in this category </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 47.76pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Introducing a requirement for homes to have a ‘missing prevention policy’, with homes required to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensure that this is agreed with the police (we are reviewing whether to change this to homes gaining the views of local services where reasonably practicable)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.75pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.76pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Requiring DCS approval of decisions to place a child in a distant placement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o address concerns about DCS capacity, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we plan to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> clear in guidance that the DCS is responsible for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘ensuring that an informed and proper decision has been reached and that any placement of a child in a distant out of authority placement is in the child’s best interests and will meet their needs’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">; and</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 47.08pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Requiring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a location risk assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We will take further time to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in light of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stakeholder concerns the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">next steps </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on this issue and the development of clear guidance on this.</span></li></ol><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are a number of proposals that did not command </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sufficient support to implement them. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roposal to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">require </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">managers to have level 5 qualification </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">before</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> being appointed to a registered manager’s post</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would not be feasible, given that this qualification needs to be compl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eted while in a management role.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The proposal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for authorities to quality assure providers’ proposed Regulation 33 visits schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> did not gain support as providers felt that this function was already carried out through inspection</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  We do not plan to take th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> forward.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are pleased to provide the Committee with the full </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">set of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consultation response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are enclosed with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this document. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are planning to introduce most of our planned revisions to the regulatory framework early in the New Year.</span></li></ol><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 7.1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 7.1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 7.1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Inspection</span></h2><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Regulatory changes above are important measures which will improve the operation of the existing system. However, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t is the Government’s view, shared by Ofsted, that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more fundamental change is needed.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he current framework of regulation and inspection limits our capacity to set ambitious objectives to ensure that all homes provide reliable high quality support to each child in their care.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> To address this, the Children and Families Bill </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">presently before Parliament now includes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a number of amendments to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Care Standards Act 2000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. These amendments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enable the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulation and inspection framework </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be moved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">away from one that rests on national minimum standards (NMS)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to one that sets high standards for residential care </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">settings, enabling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> them </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to offer the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> support required </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by their children to help them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> achieve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their full potential</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Broadly speaking, these changes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 50.46pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nable the Secretary of State to make regulations that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prescribe objectives which must be met by children’s homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; and </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 50.46pt; padding-left:6.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enable the Secretary of State to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">develop of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new quality </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">standards which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> explain and supplement the above regulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> allow future Ofsted inspection of children’s homes to assess how each home meets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We want to support innovation in the sector, stripping away much of the current overly bureaucratic framework which sets out very detailed requirements on how homes must operate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We intend to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">replac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this with clear standards that homes must achieve but which leaves them much more discretion on how they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have worked very closely with Ofsted to develop the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se changes, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supports our plans to move</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> away from a regulatory system based on minimum standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We will work with key partners to develop this revised framework including: local authorities; children’s homes providers; voluntary organisations and children. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These will include, for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Skilled leadership and management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that demonstrates a strong sense of direction, with commitment to meeting the needs of the children the home cares for. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">High </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">quality education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> either offered by those homes that are registered as schools or through the establishment of constructive relationships with local school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, so children are enabled to access the best education available.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Approaches to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">health care</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or specific mental health</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> interventions based on clear evidence of effectiveness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Effective and explicit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">safeguarding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> arrangements in place,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> including arra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ngements to minimise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">children running away.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Staff capacity to support and encourage positive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">socially aware behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – that proactively diverts them from offending behaviour. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n expectation that each home offers children an enabling, encouraging, environment in which each child is offered the opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">enjoy and achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and reach their potential</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our aim is to consult on this revised framework in the summer of 2014.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Workforce</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Children’s homes need skilled, motivated, confident </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who have the breadth of expertise and knowledge required to work with children and young people with a range of needs. Staff </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be able to understand and have appropriate strategies to respond to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">range of emotional behavioural and social problems that young people may present</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have the skills to develop effective relationships with children who may find this challenging and be able to work effectively as a team.  They will need to be able to establish strong relationships with other professionals (who are likely to have a high level of qualifications and occupational competence) in order to improve outcomes for children and provide stability and continuity of care.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The final report of the expert group found that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">qualification,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specialist knowledge and skill in the children’s home workforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is insufficient, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">especially given the level of vulnerability and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increasingly challenging needs</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our aim is that all staff and managers of homes will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have a higher level of skills, knowledge and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> qualification. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We will achieve this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by reviewing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the current content and level of the qualifications required by those working in and managing children’s homes, explor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> whether higher level qualifications are required and what such qualifications might contain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who might deliver these, and what any implementation issues in respect of such an ambition might be. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have put together </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> working group consisting of academics,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> voluntary sector,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> private providers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">kills for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> bodies. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">group is tasked with helping the Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">develop proposals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the training and development of the workforce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Summer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2014. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> As part of this we are working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the group to review the content and appropriateness of the principal existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">care home </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">qualifications (which are at levels 3 and 5 of the  Qualification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (QCF)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) and will work with those responsible for their content and delivery to take forward any necessary revisions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Alongside this we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have contracted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with TNS BMRB/NCB to undertake research to better understand the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">skills of the children’s homes workforce. The research aims to identify the key needs of managers and staff in meeting resident children’s needs, and review emerging proposals on qualifications, skills and training reforms being developed by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">workforce</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> working group.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The research will be carried out in three parts; a national census of the workforce, a study of the skills and knowledge of staff in different types of homes and whether these are sufficient to enable staff to meet the needs of the children placed in the home and a final stage to test out emerging proposals with a wide group of partners. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Work on the census has begun and early findings are promising.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our aim is that a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">report on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ke</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y findings will be published </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in Summer 2014</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and will inform proposals for change in this area.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 7.1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Information, accountability, and the operation of the children’s homes market </span></h2><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As set out above, local authority-run homes now account for a minority of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1,718 children’s homes in England. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The private sector includes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a variety of ownership structures, including private equity and venture capital, family-owned companies and individual social entrepreneurs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The development of this mixed economy of provision poses significant challenges. In the first instance, the Government has moved to increase the availability of information in this area, raising the accountability of those responsible for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the commissioning and delivery of these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> services. Early in 2013 we amended Regulations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the sharing of data between Ofsted and the Government; and in September 2013, the Government published a Children’s Homes Data Pack. This contained the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> full</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">est</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> information possible about the location, ownership and quality of children’s homes in England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; including, for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the first time, the inspection judgements awarded to the homes of the largest private providers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ata </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was also published showing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the geographical distribution of homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; how LAs vary in their use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">placements far from a child’s home</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and information on the cost of provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The data and information that we now have is far from perfect, but certain issues around the commissioning and supply of children’s homes stand out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in particular, the supply of places in children’s homes does not match need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there are too many located in the most disadvantaged areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and there is a lack of robust information on what options are available to commissioners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  The system is insufficiently focused on outcomes – what is achieved for the large sums of money expended on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">residential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">care? These issues and others were highlighted in important research published by the Local Government Association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> earlier this year</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is complex territory, but as the Secretary of State set out in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a recent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">speech</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it is an area ripe for innovation - for both commissioners and providers to aim higher, to emulate the very best of national and international practice and reshape residential care in this country to put the safety and care of children above all other considerations. We are working with competition experts and economic regulators, as well as private and local authority providers, to determine how best we can improve the commissioning system in this market</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we will welcome the committee’s views on how to achieve this. </span></li></ol><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Conclu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">sion</span></h2><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Children’s residential care must change.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We need to see better practice, sharper and more structured accountability, and greater innovation. This paper has set out the Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approach to reforming the regulatory and inspection framework, workforce and the functioning of the market in order to achieve this, and we welcome the Committee’s interest in this crucially important area. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2014</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfE Children’s Homes Data Pack 2013</span></li></ol><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Berridge, D., Biehal, N. and Henry, L. 2012, Living in Children's Residential Homes Research Report, DFE-RR201</span></li></ol><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfE Children’s Homes Data Pack 2013.</span></li></ol><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ibid</span></li></ol><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Expert group on the quality of children’s homes - final report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. DfE 2013. </span></li></ol><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Action Research into the Strategic Commissioning of Children’s Residential Care Homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">; f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">inal report to the Local Government Association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. OPM June 2013</span></li></ol><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Michael Gove speech to the NSPCC: getting it right for children in need. Available at</span><span style="font-famil